/*
=========================================================
NOTES: Subarrays with Exactly K Distinct Integers
=========================================================

âŒ Why direct sliding window fails?
----------------------------------
When we try to count subarrays directly when distinct == k,
multiple subarrays ending at the same index get counted again,
leading to OVERCOUNT.

Example:
nums = [1,2,1,2], k = 2

At j = 3:
Valid subarrays:
[1,2,1,2], [2,1,2], [1,2]

But counting (j - i + 1) blindly also includes:
[2] âŒ (only 1 distinct)

---------------------------------------------------------

âœ… Correct Strategy:
-------------------
Instead of counting EXACTLY K directly,
count using subtraction:

exactlyK = atMost(K) - atMost(K - 1)

---------------------------------------------------------

ðŸ§  atMost(K) Sliding Window Logic:
---------------------------------
- Expand right pointer j
- Track frequency using hashmap
- If distinct > K â†’ shrink from left
- At each j, add (j - i + 1)

This counts ALL valid subarrays ending at j with <= K distinct

---------------------------------------------------------

ðŸ§® Mathematical Reason:
----------------------
Every subarray with exactly K distinct
is included in atMost(K)
but excluded from atMost(K - 1)

So subtraction isolates exactly K

---------------------------------------------------------

ðŸ“Œ Key Takeaways:
----------------
âœ” Exactly K cannot be solved reliably with a single window
âœ” Difference of two atMost windows is mandatory
âœ” (j - i + 1) works ONLY for atMost problems
âœ” This is a classic interview-level sliding window pattern

=========================================================
*/
